  "text": "Postcolonial feminist Chandra Talpade Mohanty describes colonisation as a 'relation of structural domination, and a suppression-often violent-of the heterogeneity of the subject(s) in question'. [CITATION_1] Mohanty was talking about how 'third world' women of colour were collapsed into a homogenous category by western feminist thought, but we can apply a similar perspective to the doctor-patient relationship. Mohanty warns us against the construction of groups of people as a coherent, unified entity that can be understood, represented and grouped. This warning is akin to what Nigerian author Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie calls the 'danger of the single story', or the risk of universalising the experiences of groups of people based on the specific and narrowly constructed experience of an individual. [CITATION_2] This recalls the attempt to bring 'the patient voice' into educational initiatives, as though there were a single voice to be captured.",
